response:
 First, let's have a look at this piece of information: $f(q(1)) = -3$. We would like to plug in $1$ (\textit{i.e.} $q(1)$) to the function $q(x) = bx + 1$ to get the value of $q(1)$. 
\begin{align} q(1) &= b(1) + 1 \\ &= b + 1  \tag{1} \end{align}
Next, let's plug in the answer we obtained from (1) into $f(x) = x - 3$:
\begin{align} f(q(1)) &= f(b + 1) \tag{2} \end{align}
Also $f(q(1)) = -3$.
\begin{align} f(b + 1) &= -3 \tag{3} \end{align}
Now, $f(x) = x - 3$. So,
\begin{align} f(b + 1) &= (b + 1) - 3 \\  &= b - 2 \tag{4} \end{align}
But, $f(b + 1) = -3$. So by (3) and (4),
\begin{align} b - 2 &= -3 \\ &\boxed{ \text{ therefore } } \\ b &= -1 \tag{5} \end{align} <answer> $–1$ </answer>

